<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How long is the cooling-off period in a Queensland residential property contract?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "In Queensland, residential property buyers have a 5-business-day cooling-off period after the buyer receives the signed contract of sale. If the buyer terminates during this period, they forfeit 0.25% of the purchase price to the seller as a penalty. The cooling-off period runs from the day the buyer receives the fully signed contract, not from exchange or the date the contract was signed."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can a seller cool off or exit a Queensland property contract?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. The cooling-off period in Queensland only benefits the buyer. Once a seller signs a contract, they are bound by it. A seller cannot use the cooling-off period to exit a contract if they receive a higher offer or change their mind. Sellers who need to exit an unconditional contract face serious legal and financial consequences, so it is critical to only sign a contract you intend to honour."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does the cooling-off period apply to auction sales in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. Contracts formed at auction in Queensland are not subject to the cooling-off period. When the hammer falls and the buyer signs the contract at auction, that contract is immediately binding on both parties with no right of termination under the cooling-off provisions. This is one of the practical reasons sellers choose auction as a method of sale where market conditions support it."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

